Small question: should this be `incompRel_refl` or `IncompRel.refl`? Likewise, should the version with implicit arguments (which I haven't added yet) be `incompRel_rfl` or `IncompRel.rfl`?

I suspect the convention we're using on `AntisymmRel` currently is wrong on both counts, but I want to make sure.
`IncompRel.refl`/`IncompRel.rfl` so that we can use it with anonymous dot notation
These lemmas will be annoying to use. Can we have applied versions?

I'd suggest swapping the definition with the one coming from the RHS of the lemma. This way:
* You don't need `incompRel_iff` as it's just the equational lemma now
* `simp [‚Üê antisymmRel_compl]` won't loop anymore
Can this move out of the `Relation` section? It's supposed to be about an arbitrary relation, not about `LE`
I'll put them at the very end, like I did with `AntisymmRel`.

But then why not do it correctly? You already have a `Preorder` section
```suggestion

end Relation

section LE

variable [LE Œ±]

theorem IncompRel.not_le (h : IncompRel (¬∑ ‚â§ ¬∑) a b) : ¬¨ a ‚â§ b := h.1
theorem IncompRel.not_ge (h : IncompRel (¬∑ ‚â§ ¬∑) a b) : ¬¨ b ‚â§ a := h.2
theorem LE.le.not_incompRel (h : a ‚â§ b) : ¬¨ IncompRel (¬∑ ‚â§ ¬∑) a b := fun h' ‚Ü¶ h'.not_le h

end LE

section Preorder
```
Alright, I've updated the `Antisymmetrization` file to match.
